    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my civil eng exam and im a bit confused. if concrete is already really strong, why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside it for foundations? like what is the actual relationship between the compressive strength of the concrete and the tensile strength of the steel?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Concrete is incredibly strong in compression, which is great for holding things up, but it's actually quite weak when it comes to tension, like when it's being pulled apart. This is where the steel rebar comes in, acting like the muscle of the foundation. The relationship is a perfect partnership, as the high-strength steel is excellent at handling those tensile forces that concrete can't manage on its own. They work together to create a composite material that is much stronger overall.",
      "source": "target",
